Local Engagement as a Countermeasure Against Populism
PARIS – The parties once dominating Western democracies have been shaken to their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leadership of once-dominant parties wavers between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to recognize a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters of the opposition as "pitiable," just as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared by the populist wave to launch a counteroffensive.
Neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the stagnated political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize, and this begins with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographical inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that really matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are all alone in the woods and wonder where everyone has gone.
Social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed off course.
The gap between her objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some prosperous, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
However, until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron implemented it, no national government leader had ever enacted tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of the French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the surveyors then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes from his opponents; however, the laughter faded quickly with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and rally the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to gain and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Trotz these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and launch petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Today, citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights and not as peasants in the chess game of others.
Moreover, the governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the tough lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The today's most important political challenges – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions solely from national governments.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the entry barriers for political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and consolidated support networks.
Those who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well do not need a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements must therefore be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not only on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "backoffice"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche! we refer to this as local citizen initiatives.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, the goal is to offer solutions tailored to local problems in order to strengthen the communities.
Such projects should today be considered indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding ways for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And as they demonstrate their reform policies daily "live," the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can attract people to their side.
Reconnecting with voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive policies locally.
